pullRequest.body:
The set of reals `t` where `exp (t * X)` is integrable is an interval containing 0. Also prove integrability of other function for a parameter in that interval.

Rename Probability/Moments to Probability/Moments/Basic

Thanks for the review and proof suggestions! This is now ready for review again.
I plan to add generalizations of this lemma for other points than 0 :
```lean
lemma mem‚Ñíp_of_mem_interior_integrableExpSet (h : 0 ‚àà interior (integrableExpSet X Œº)) (p : ‚Ñù‚â•0) :
    Mem‚Ñíp X p Œº :=
```
Those generalizations will state that X is in Lp for a tilted measure, but I'll do that in a later PR.

awaiting-author
I saw things I should improve while working on related code.

I wonder if it's worth giving a name to `{t | Integrable (fun œâ ‚Ü¶ exp (t * X œâ)) Œº}` and formulating results in terms of this (and state explicitely that this is set is convex). What do you think?
The exponential is called `exp` before, is there a reason you switch to `rexp` here?
I guess I copied something from the infoview, which used rexp. I'll switch it back to exp.
Is it easy to also derive a `memLp` statement from this one or the next one (for real exponents, not only integers ones)?

I'm not sure you need `1 ‚â§ p` here. Quick proof sketch: one has x \le e^x for all real x. So c x \le e ^ {c x}, i.e., x \le c^{-1} e^ {c x}. Applying this to x and -x gives |x| \le c^{-1} max (e^{c x}, e^{-c x}), and then |x|^p \le c^{-p} max (e^{p c x}, e^{-p c x}). Then for any p (be it larger or smaller than 1), you can choose c small enough so that e^{p c X} and e^{-p c X} are integrable, and then you deduce that |X|^p is integrable. This has the advantage to avoid the dance with integer parts also...
